          "body": "Paul piles up four Old Testament quotations — one from each of the three sections of the Hebrew canon plus a second Psalm — to prove that Gentile inclusion was never an afterthought. **Psalm 18:49 / 2 Samuel 22:50** (v. 9): David, the Davidic king, praises God *among* the Gentiles. **Deuteronomy 32:43** (v. 10): Moses calls Gentiles to rejoice *with* God's people. **Psalm 117:1** (v. 11): all peoples praise the Lord. **Isaiah 11:10** (v. 12): the Root of Jesse rises to rule the Gentiles, who hope in Him. Law (Moses), Prophets (Isaiah), and Writings (Psalms) speak with one voice. The exegetical move is breathtaking — Paul shows that the Gentile mission is the consummation of Israel's own scriptures, not a deviation from them. This is the same hermeneutic Paul has used throughout Romans (cf. 3:10-18; 9:25-29; 10:18-21), but here it climaxes in worship — *all peoples praise Him*."
